Midgaard's relationship to the Great Northern Forest is primarily commercial and administrative. The Granite Arcade serves as administrative hub for all forest-related commerce, contracts, and ranger writs. Road wardens carry Midgaard guild chits and report to Granite Arcade offices. Lamp-keepers are paid from Midgaard's civic treasury. Timber surveyors from the Woodwrights Guild conduct annual assessments; unauthorized felling means tool confiscation and route ban. The Ashfall Monsoon ash winters blanketed the canopy, poisoned shallow streams, killed an estimated third of large game, and generated the first formal Passage Tithe system. The Reckoning faction's critique of the Granite Arcade trade ledger — specifically the entry "forty iron bars and six condemned debtors" transferred to "the mountain academy" — implicates the northern forest route as part of a condemned-labor transfer corridor during the Continuity era.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's presence is strongest in the northern crown and checkpoint rings. The Jade Magistracy's Wardens of Iron maintain a rotating garrison at the northern customs post on seasonal rotation. Waystations use strict inventory chalkboards, sealed ration lockers, and covenant plaques. Dispute circles use witness stones mirroring Kowloon's public-judgment ethic. The Oath-Crossing negotiation was contentious: Kowloon demanded binding arbitration enforceable by the Jade Magistracy; Midgaard refused single-city jurisdiction over neutral ground. Cairn-Keeper elder Toreth Gael's compromise — witness judgment at standing stones, verdicts carved into stone rather than filed in either city's courts — became the warden tribunal system. Northern patrol captains record incidents in duplicate: one ledger for Kowloon, one for shared forest archives.

